** Abstract **

Gallstone disease (GSD) is a gastrointestinal condition marked by the development of hardened substances within the gallbladder, representing a notable health challenge. The causes of GSD are numerous, involving a complicated interaction between environmental factors and genetic predispositions. The ATP8B1 gene encodes a P4-ATPase flippase, which is crucial for preserving the lipid asymmetry of the hepatocanalicular membrane; impairments in this gene are recognized as a contributing factor to intrahepatic cholestasis. Although mutations in ATP8B1 are well-established in severe liver diseases in children, their involvement in gallstone disease that arises in adulthood is still not investigated, especially in the South Asian demographic.
This study aimed to explore the possible link between the ATP8B1 gene single nucleotide polymorphism (SNP) rs766737165 (T>A) and the risk of gallstone disease in the Pakistani population. We conducted a case-control study with 104 participants, including 75 gallstone patients and 29 healthy controls from various regions and ethnic backgrounds. We extracted DNA from blood samples and used the Tetra-Primer Amplification Refractory Mutation System Polymerase Chain Reaction (TETRA-ARMS PCR) method for genotyping the rs766737165 (T>A) variant.
Demographic analysis showed a higher number of females in the disease group, making up 76%. Genotypic analysis found that the wild-type genotype (TT) was present in everyone who was successfully genotyped. The variant allele (A) was not found in either the case or control groups. This suggests that this locus is monomorphic in the population we studied.
In conclusion, my findings indicate that the ATP8B1 rs766737165 (T>A) variant is not a significant genetic factor for cholelithiasis in this specific Pakistani group. However, because ATP8B1 plays an important role in bile balance, these results do not rule out the possibility that other variants in the gene may be involved. I recommend future research using Whole Exome Sequencing (WES) in larger groups to better understand the genetic role of ATP8B1 in gallstone disease in Pakistan. 
